        "is_accepted": true,
        "last_activity_date": 1380367448,
        "creation_date": 1380366276,
        "body": "<pre><code>String unicodeString = new String(currentByteArray, \"Windows-1257\");\nbyte[] result = unicodeString.getBytes(\"ISO-8859-13\");\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>or<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>PrintWriter out = new PrintWriter(file, \"ISO-8859-13\");\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Java is very simple: String/Reader&amp;Writer is Unicode text capable to contain all characters.\nAnd binary byte[]s/InputStream&amp;OutputStream is for binary data.<\/p>\n\n<p>Hence the String constructor for bytes needs the original encoding of those bytes,\nand getting bytes needs the encoding where those bytes should be in.<\/p>\n\n<p>Be aware that there are overloaded versions with one parameter, without encoding. That uses the platform encoding; not-portable.<\/p>\n",
